<l>vaḷḷukira vayalāmai</l>
<l>veḷḷakaṭu kaṇṭaṉṉa</l>
<l>vīṅkuvicip putuppōrvait</l>
<l>teṇkaṇ mākkiṇai yiyakki yeṉṟu</l>
<l>māṟukoṇṭōr matiliṭaṟi</l>
<l>nīṟāṭiya naṟuṅkavuḷa</l>
<l>pūmpoṟi paṇaiyeruttiṉa</l>
<l>vēṟuvēṟu parantiyaṅki</l>
<l>vēntuṭaimiḷai yayalparakku</l>
<l>mēntukōṭ ṭirumpiṇar taṭakkait</l>
<l>tiruntutoḻiṟ palapakaṭu</l>
<l>pakaippula maṉṉar paṇitiṟai tantuniṉ</l>
<l>ṉakaippula vāṇar nalkura vakaṟṟi</l>
<l>mikappoliyartaṉ cēvaṭi yattaiyeṉ</l>
<l>ṟiyāṉicaippi ṉaṉinaṉṟeṉāp</l>
<l>palapiṟa vāḻtta viruntō reṉkō<gap quantity="15" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>maruvaviṉaka rakaṉ<gap quantity="33" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>tiruntukaḻaṟ cēvaṭi kuṟukal vēṇṭi</l>
<l>veṉṟiraṅkum viṟaṉmuraciṉō</l>
<l>ṉeṉciṟumaiyi ṉiḻittunōkkāṉ</l>
<l>taṉperumaiyiṟ ṟakavunōkkik</l>
<l>kuṉṟuṟaḻnta kaḷiṟeṉkō</l>
<l>koyyuḷaiya māveṉkō</l>
<l>maṉṟuniṟaiyu niraiyeṉkō</l>
<l>maṉaikkaḷamaroṭu kaḷameṉkō</l>
<l>vāṅkavai, kaṉaveṉa maruḷa vallē naṉavi</l>
<l>ṉalki yōṉē nacaicā ṟōṉṟa</l>
<l>lūḻi vāḻi pūḻiyar perumakaṉ</l>
<l>piṇarmarup piyāṉaic cerumiku nōṉṟāṭ</l>
<l>celvak kaṭuṅkō vāḻi yāta</l>
<l>ṉoṉṉāt tevva ruyarkuṭai paṇittivaṇ</l>
<l>viṭuvar mātō neṭitē ni<gap quantity="19" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>pullilai vañcip puṟamati lalaikkuṅ</l>
<l>kalleṉ porunai maṇaliṉu māṅkaṭ</l>
<l>pallūr cuṟṟiya kaḻaṉi</l>
<l>yellām viḷaiyu nelliṉum palavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Always stirring [my] big Kiṇai drum with a clear eye, (4)</l>
<l>with a new covering with taught leather straps, (3)</l>
<l>that looks like the white belly (2)</l>
<l>of the sharp-nailed tortoise in the pond, (1)</l>
<l>when I sing: (15a) </l>
<l>“Having dispelled the poverty of you Vāṇar with smiling wisdom (13)</l>
<l>by giving [them] the humble tribute of the kings from enemy regions, (12)</l>
<l>[that is,] the many [elephant] bulls of perfect training (11)</l>
<l>with large rough broad trunks [and] eminent tusks, (10)</l>
<l>who spread in the neighbourhood of the king’s enclosure (9)</l>
<l>after having struck the fortification of those who took up opposition, (5)</l>
<l>with fragrant cheeks that were bathed in ashes, (6)</l>
<l>with flower-dotted bulky necks, (7)</l>
<l>stirring and fanning out one after another, (8)</l>
<l>may his red feet much flourish.”, (14)</l>
<l>	thinking that is is very good, (15b)</l>
<l>shall I say “there where those who praise many other things”? (16)</l>
<l>while … </l>
<l>come together, in the pleasing mansion, wide………. (17f.)</l>
<l>Wanting to come neat the red feet with perfect anklets, (18)</l>
<l>the one with a victorious drum that sounds victoriously, (19)</l>
<l>who does not look disparagingly at my smallness (20)</l>
<l>shall I look at the fitness of his greatness (21)</l>
<l>[and] speak of [his] elephant that is like a hill? (22)</l>
<l>Shall I speak of [his] big horse with trimmed mane? (23)</l>
<l>Shall I speak of the herd that fills the manger? (24)</l>
<l>Shall I speak of the threshing floor with those who thresh by the house? (25)</l>
<l>While being strongly confused as by a dream about those that are such, in reality (26)</l>
<l>he is the one who granted. Appearance worthy to be longed for. (27)</l>
<l>may you live for aeons, great son of the Pūḻiyar. (28)</l>
<l>[On?] and elephant with rough tusks [and] fight-lusty sturdy feet, (29)</l>
<l>Celvakkaṭuṅkō Vāḻiyātaṉ, (30)</l>
<l>Will the enemies, who were in disagreement, having been humbled here under [his] high parasol, (31)</l>
<l>not let go for a long time? ….. (32)</l>
<l>more than the [grains of] sand in the noisy Porunai (34a-c)</l>
<l>that slaps against the out fortification of Vañci with puny leaves (~ the city, not the tree), (33)</l>
<l>more than the [grains] of paddy that all ripen (36)</l>
<l>in the fields that encircle the many villages there. (34df.)</l>
</lg>
